fields.name: LEVANDER "VAN" SMITH, JR.
fields.bio: Levander Smith was appointed to the Circuit Court in early 2019 and currently oversees cases in the Domestic Violence Division. Prior to his appointment to the bench, he had two stints as an attorney with the Illinois Department of Children and Family Services, first in the 1990s and then again from 2011 to 2019. In between, he spent four years as a prosecutor, first in St. Louis County and then in Cook County. He was also an assistant attorney general in Missouri, where he worked on worker’s compensation cases.
fields.notable: His campaign is mostly self-funded. He had loaned his campaign over $60,000 as of Dec. 31, 2019.

fields.name: MARY THERESE QUINN
fields.bio: Mary Quinn spent over two decades in the Cook County State’s Attorney’s Office, where she prosecuted a wide variety of felony cases. She currently works in private practice as a criminal defense attorney. Quinn previously ran for judge in the 15th subcircuit three times but failed to win the Democratic primary on each occasion.

fields.name: MEGAN KATHLEEN MULAY
fields.bio: Mulay began her legal career by joining the Cook County State’s Attorney’s Office, where she has been since. She is currently the first chair attorney at the Leighton Criminal Courthouse, in the criminal prosecutions bureau. She currently oversees the prosecution and management of over 300 active felony cases.

fields.name: SUZANNE THERESE McENEELY
fields.bio: Suzanne McEneely has spent her career as public defender, having joined the office soon after becoming authorized to practice law in 2002. She has worked in a variety of roles within the public defender’s office, including the abuse and neglect division, the domestic violence division, and now the criminal division. She currently works at the Skokie Courthouse.
fields.notable: McEneely has filed for a notice of self-funding for her campaign, meaning she has donated enough money to her own campaign that fundraising caps for the entire race have been removed. Her family has donated over $150,000 for the purposes of her election.

fields.name: JACQUELINE MARIE GRIFFIN
fields.bio: Jacqueline Griffin has been an assistant state’s attorney since she became a lawyer in 2005. For the past two years, Jacqueline has been a trial specialist in the sexual assault and domestic violence unit of the felony trial division. Griffin comes from a family of Chicago firefighters and police union members.

fields.name: ARTHUR D. SUTTON
fields.bio: Arthur Sutton is currently an attorney in private practice, where he practices civil litigation and criminal defense. He has previously worked in a variety of roles in the Department of Corrections, including time as a correctional officer. He began his legal career as a Cook County public defender in the mid-1990s. He previously ran for judge in 2006.
fields.notable:
Sutton resigned from his position as Deputy Director of the Parole Division of the Illinois Department of Corrections in February 2015 after failing to secure his government issued gun on two occasions. The first came in 2014 when his son, then 17, took the gun and shot himself in the ankle, and the second happened in February 2015 when his son once again took the gun and used it in an armed robbery in which someone was shot in the leg.

In 2003, Sutton received a 90-day stayed suspension from the Illinois Supreme Court. The Attorney Registration and Disciplinary Commission concluded that Sutton had violated multiple ethical policies by improperly managing settlement money and mixing his personal funds with settlement funds.

fields.name: CELESTIA L. MAYS
fields.bio: Celestia Mays was appointed to the bench at the end of 2018 and began hearing cases in the Municipal Department in January 2019. Prior to her appointment, she focused on family and estate law as an attorney in private practice. Mays also previously served as the president of the Cook County Bar Association. She was a finalist for an associate judgeship in 2018, but she was not selected.

fields.name: JENNIFER PATRICIA CALLAHAN
fields.bio: Jennifer Callahan practices in the areas of criminal defense and transactional work as an attorney in private practice. After graduating from law school, she worked as an assistant state’s attorney, serving in the first municipal division, the narcotics prosecutions bureau, and the alternative prosecutions unit. Callahan has also worked as an administrative law judge and as retained counsel for an in-house insurance defense firm defending employment claims.
fields.notable: Callahan has filed a notice of self-funding and has loaned her campaign $100,000.

fields.name: MICHAEL O'MALLEY
fields.bio: Michael O’Malley has served as an assistant state’s attorney for the past 14 years. Currently, he works in the civil rights and torts division of the Cook County State’s Attorney’s office. He has also worked in the special prosecutions bureau, prosecuting public corruption, and has prosecuted child sex crimes. Prior to becoming a lawyer, O’Malley was a financial analyst for JPMorgan Chase. O’Malley ran unsuccessfully for judge in 2016 and 2018.
fields.notable: O’Malley’s campaign is largely self-funded. He has loaned his campaign committee more than $68,000.

fields.name: TERESA MOLINA
fields.bio: Teresa Molina was appointed to the bench in July 2019 and she currently works in the First Municipal Division, where she oversees traffic cases. Prior to her appointment, she led real estate prosecutions at the Illinois Department of Financial and Professional Regulation. For the first 15 years of her legal career, Molina was an Cook County assistant state’s attorney, where she worked in the felony trial division, the grand jury unit, and the felony review unit.

fields.name: DANIEL L. COLLINS
fields.bio: Daniel Collins works in private practice, specializing in worker compensation and other business and employment litigation. He started his career as an assistant state’s attorney in the Cook County State’s Attorney’s office. Collins previously ran in the 2018 Democratic primary for the 4th Subcircuit under the name Danny Collins. He was elected in 2019 to the Board of Commissioners of the Park District of La Grange.

fields.name: U. O'NEAL
fields.bio: U. O’Neal has worked as an attorney and principal partner in his own law firm since 1993. He has practiced in a range of different areas of law, including corporate, criminal defense and civil rights. O’Neal is also a certified mandatory arbitrator for the circuit courts of Cook County. He previously ran as Ubi O’Neal in the 2018 Democratic primary for the 2nd subcircuit and lost. Before he ran for office, he was known as Ubochi Osuji.
fields.notable: O’Neal was censured for legal misconduct by the Illinois Supreme Court in 1999, after he directed someone to fraudulently endorse a settlement check so that he could be paid for his work. The Attorney Registration and Disciplinary Commission chose censure over more severe remedies, noting that “his improper conduct is attributable to lack of experience and poor judgment rather than an intent to deny any party a share of the settlement proceeds.”

fields.name: DAN WALSH
fields.bio: Dan Walsh has worked as an assistant public defender in Cook County for most of his career. He represents defendants in felony cases at the Maywood Courthouse. Prior to his current role, he spent time working for the State Appellate Defender.

fields.name: JOHN O'MEARA
fields.bio: John O’Meara is currently an administrative law judge for the Illinois Department of Labor. He was appointed as a Circuit Court judge in the 4th subcircuit in 2016, but he was unseated in the 2018 Democratic primary by Elizabeth Ciaccia-Lezza. After graduating from law school, O’Meara worked as an assistant corporation counsel for the City of Chicago. Prior to his appointment to the bench, O’Meara worked as an attorney in private practice for nearly two decades, where he specialized in civil litigation.

fields.name: AMANDA "MANDY" PILLSBURY
fields.bio: Amanda Pillsbury has worked as an assistant state’s attorney for her entire 15-year legal career. She currently serves in the felony trial division.
fields.notable: Pillsbury unsuccessfully ran for a circuit court seat in 2018. In that election, multiple bar associations made a mention of her temperament. The ISBA found opinions on her diligence and temperament were “divided,” and the CCL said she could be “abrasive with opposing counsel.” Both these organizations found her “Not Qualified” in 2018.

fields.name: KEELY PATRICIA HILLISON
fields.bio: Keely Hillison has been an attorney for 30 years, first at Parrillo Weiss LLC, a Chicago law firm, where she was a partner, and now for her own firm. At Parrillo Weiss, Hillison supervised the firm’s insurance law and appellate practices. Since 2000, she has also served as an arbitrator in the Circuit Court of Cook County. Hillison ran unsuccessfully for a circuit court seat in 2018.

fields.name: LAURA AYALA-GONZALEZ
fields.bio: Laura Ayala-Gonzalez currently works as an supervising assistant state's attorney in the felony trial unit. She has spent her entire 16-year legal career in the State’s Attorney’s office, where she has served in the juvenile justice bureau, the gangs and complex homicide unit, and as a deputy supervisor in the felony review unit.

fields.name: SHEREE DESIREE HENRY
fields.bio: Sheree Henry was appointed to the bench in July 2019. Prior to her appointment, Henry worked as an assistant public defender for two decades. Before that, she spent three years as an assistant public guardian, representing children in abuse and neglect cases. Henry currently oversees traffic cases at the Daley Center.
fields.notable: Henry served in the Illinois Army National Guard for eight years.

fields.name: ELIZABETH ANNE WALSH
fields.bio: Elizabeth Walsh has worked as a trial attorney in private practice throughout her career. She focuses on civil law and has defended individuals and businesses facing lawsuits in civil court.

fields.name: HEATHER ANNE KENT
fields.bio: Heather Kent has spent her career as an assistant state’s attorney. She is currently assigned to the felony trial division, but previously tried cases in both misdemeanor and child protection courtrooms.

fields.name: JAMES T. DERICO, JR.
fields.bio: James Derico was appointed to the Circuit Court in December 2018, and serves in the Municipal division. Prior to his appointment, he spent much of his career in private practice, where he specialized in business, real estate and tax law. Derico also previously volunteered for Chicago Volunteer Legal Services, an organization that offers pro bono legal representation to low-income clients in the Chicago area.

fields.name: LLOYD JAMES BROOKS
fields.bio: Lloyd Brooks was appointed to the Circuit Court in November 2018. Prior to his appointment, Brooks worked in private practice, specializing in consumer protection and mortgage foreclosure defense. Brooks also practiced in insurance law and commercial litigation. He currently oversees cases in the Municipal Division at the Daley Center.
fields.notable: Brooks’ campaign is mostly self-funded. He has loaned his campaign $90,000.

fields.name: ELIZABETH "BETH" RYAN
fields.bio: Elizabeth Ryan is currently an attorney at the law office of Elizabeth C. Ryan, specializing in personal injury law. She has been a practicing attorney since 2006. She previously worked at Newman Boyer & Statham and clerked for Cook County Circuit Court judge Martin Agran.
fields.notable: Ryan has filed a notice of self-funding, and she and her husband, Clancy, have contributed over $150,000 to her campaign, thus removing the fundraising cap for the entire race.

fields.name: LYNN WEAVER BOYLE
fields.bio: Lynn Weaver Boyle was appointed to the Circuit Court in December 2018. Prior to her appointment, Boyle worked at the Chicago office of Grotefeld Hoffman, LLP, a national law firm, where she represented clients in commercial litigation. She began her legal career in the Cook County State’s Attorney’s Office, where she worked for almost a decade as an assistant state’s attorney in the criminal division. She currently hears municipal civil cases and traffic matters at the Daley Center.
fields.notable: Boyle’s election committee has raised over $250,000, most of which comes from her family.

fields.name: AILEEN BHANDARI
fields.bio: Aileen Bhandari has been an assistant state’s attorney for the past 16 years. She currently serves in the Felony Trial Division, where she has prosecuted a wide range of felony cases including violent and white-collar crimes. She was selected last year as a finalist for a Cook County Circuit Court associate judgeship but did not make the final list for appointment. According to her campaign site, Bhandari has held leadership roles in several legal organizations, including the South Asian Bar Association and the Filipino Lawyers Association of Chicago.

fields.name: ARACELI REYES DE LA CRUZ
fields.currentJob: General counsel, Acero Charter School Network
fields.bio: Araceli De La Cruz is currently general counsel for the Acero Charter School Network. Prior to that she worked for the Illinois Department of Financial and Professional Regulation as the chief of general prosecutions and for the Chicago Transit Authority as a chief compliance officer and deputy chief of staff. De La Cruz started her career as an assistant state’s attorney. Over the course of a decade at the Cook County State’s Attorney’s Office, she served in six different divisions, including the Juvenile Justice Bureau, the Sex Crimes Division, and the Felony Review Division.
fields.notable: De La Cruz is the Democratic Party’s slated candidate for this race and her campaign is mostly self-funded. She loaned more than $70,000 to her campaign and has donated $30,000 to the Cook County Democractic Party.

fields.name: ANNE SHAW
fields.bio: Anne Shaw has worked in private practice for the majority of her career. She focuses on civil cases related to human rights, commercial law and personal injury, and she founded a pro-bono legal clinic in Chinatown that generally serves immigrants. Shaw also holds a real estate license. She previously ran unsuccessfully for the Illinois General Assembly in 2018 and for alderman in 2015.
fields.notable: As previously [reported](https://www.injusticewatch.org/news/2020/judge-candidate-anne-shaw-had-real-estate-license-reprimanded-for-deceptive-practices/ "Judge candidate Anne Shaw had real estate license reprimanded for deceptive practices") by Injustice Watch, Shaw was given a reprimand on her real estate license in 2016 for “not properly supervising employees of Shaw Real Estate Group.” Multiple lawsuits accused the organization of preying on people with poor credit by demanding non-refundable fees for finding apartments. The Illinois Department of Financial and Professional Regulation accused the Shaw Real Estate Group of deceptive business practices and unprofessional conduct, leading to a suspension of the organization’s license and an $18,000 fine. Shaw claims that the investigation and lawsuits were a “coordinated effort” to delegitimize her from her 2015 electoral opponent, Alderman Proco “Joe” Moreno.

fields.name: REGINA ANN MESCALL
fields.bio: Regina Ann Mescall has worked as an assistant state’s attorney in Cook County since 2007. She currently oversees cases as the first chair felony trial assistant, responsible for the active murder cases in Cook County. Mescall began her career as an Assistant District Attorney in Albuquerque, New Mexico, where she prosecuted crimes against children for over 5 years.

fields.name: 16 judge candidates fail to win bar support, but will voters care?
SCOTT EDWARD LIPINSKI
fields.bio: Scott Edward Lipinski has been a Cook County assistant public defender since shortly after passing the bar in the early 2000s. In this role, he has worked on jury and bench trials at the Bridgeview courthouse. He has previously run unsuccessfully for multiple judicial positions, most recently attempting to unseat Cook County Circuit Court Judge Rossana Fernandez in 2016.
fields.notable: Lipinski has received poor bar ratings after other lawyers accused him of sometimes losing his temper in court proceedings. In a 2016 Injustice Watch article, he strongly [denied](https://www.injusticewatch.org/news/2016/16-judge-candidates-fail-to-win-bar-support-but-will-voters-care/ "16 judge candidates fail to win bar support, but will voters care?") these accusations and said, “I’ve always been professional to any State’s Attorney or any judge.”

fields.name: LORRAINE MARY MURPHY
fields.bio: Lorraine Murphy has spent much of her career at the Cook County State’s Attorney’s Office, where she has prosecuted a variety of different types of cases in the felony trial division. Prior to her legal career, she worked in broadcast journalism. This is Murphy’s second run for the bench after an unsuccessful bid for a 10th subcircuit seat in 2018.

fields.name: LAUREN BROUGHAM GLENNON
fields.bio: Lauren Brougham Glennon practices as a private attorney at her own firm Glennon Law, LLC.  She has worked in a number of legal areas, including property tax law. She began her career as a prosecuting attorney in the Chicago Department of Law. Glennon has worked in private practice since 2006. She previously ran in and lost the 2014 race for the 3rd Subcircuit.

fields.name: CHELSEY R. ROBINSON
fields.bio: Chelsey Robinson has worked as a private attorney for her law firm Owens & Robinson since she passed the bar in 1996. Her firm specializes in cases related to bankruptcy, domestic relations, criminal defense, personal injury and worker's compensation. She previously ran in and lost the 2016 Democratic primary for the 2nd Subcircuit. In a [questionnaire](https://www.chicagolawbulletin.com/archives/2016/03/08/savage-vacancy-3-8-16 "Chicago Daily Law Bulletin") from her previous run, Robinson described her greatest career accomplishment as “[her] representation of people of low economic status.”
fields.notable: Robinson has [defended](https://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2013/08/26/how-stop-and-frisk-works-in-chicago "Chicago Reader") low-income clients who police allegedly subjected to controversial “stop-and-frisk” searches. Her law firm’s website says that the firm provides legal consultation to “The Judge Mathis Show.”

fields.name: JAMES JOHN KNIBBS
fields.bio: James J. Knibbs is a private attorney who practices across a wide range of legal areas, including commercial litigation, civil rights defense and white-collar criminal defense. Knibbs is an of counsel attorney with Foran Glennon Palandech Ponzi & Rudloff. From 1985 to 1989, he was an assistant state's attorney in Cook County under then-Cook County State’s Attorney Richard M. Daley, before spending more than a decade in private practice, and then returning to the State's Attorney's office in various roles from 2002 until 2008 under former State’s Attorney Richard Devine, including supervisor of the Public Corruption and Financial Crimes Unit. He also taught trial advocacy at Loyola Law School from 2003 to 2009.
fields.notable: Knibbs has represented “over 60 Chicago police officers in federal lawsuits,” according to his campaign website. He also helped [prosecute](https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2006-09-09-0609090050-story.html "Charges describe a reign of terror") a case against several CPD officers in 2006. Knibbs and former State’s Attorney Richard Devine worked together in private practice for several years after they left government, as partners at Meckler Bulger Tilson.

fields.name: CAROLINE PATRICIA JAMIESON
fields.bio: Jamieson is an attorney at the Sotos Law Firm, where she represents police officers in civil rights cases and employers in employment discrimination cases. Before joining her current law firm, she worked in the areas of commercial and employment litigation. Jamieson lost the 2018 Democratic Primary for the 4th Subcircuit, appearing on the ballot as “Caroline Golden,” her married name.
fields.notable: Jamieson has faced [blowback](https://cookcountyrecord.com/stories/521383715-challenge-filed-vs-judicial-candidacy-of-lawyer-who-represented-burge-using-irish-maiden-name-on-ballot "Cook County Record article on the challendge filed against Jamieson's candidacy") for her decision to run using her maiden name after running with her married name in 2018, with some accusing her of using an Irish moniker to gain support among voters. She has also defended controversial law enforcement officials, including disgraced former Chicago police commander Jon Burge, who she represented in a civil suit in which an exoneree sought damages from the city. Jamieson received an endorsement from the Chicago chapter of the Fraternal Order of Police in her 2018 run.

fields.name: DEIDRE BAUMANN
fields.bio: Baumann runs her own practice, where she specializes in civil rights litigation, personal injury and employment discrimination. She started her career in a boutique law firm that specialized in First Amendment law. She previously worked as an arbitrator for the Circuit Court of Cook County.
fields.notable: Baumann has been heavily involved in the LGBTQ community throughout her career. According to her campaign site, she is currently on the board of the Lesbian and Gay Bar Association of Chicago and serves as vice chair of the Sexual Orientation and Gender Identity Committee of the Illinois State Bar Association.

fields.name: MAURA McMAHON ZELLER
fields.bio: Maura Zeller has been an attorney in Cook County for over 26 years, primarily in the area of child welfare and guardianship litigation. She currently represents children in child custody cases as an appointed child representative and guardian ad litem. Before that, she worked for a decade in the Office of the Public Guardian as an assistant public guardian and child representative. Zeller is the board chair of the Thrive Counseling Center in Oak Park.

fields.name: DANIEL EDWARD MALONEY
fields.bio: Judge Daniel E. Maloney presides over municipal cases at the Markham courthouse. Maloney, appointed in 2019 to a 3rd subcircuit vacancy left by the retirement of Denise K. Filan, spent the first 16 years of his career working in Cook County as an assistant state’s attorney, where he prosecuted drug cases before joining the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration as division counsel in 2017.
fields.notable: In 2009, as a Cook County prosecutor, Maloney worked with DEA agents and the State’s Attorney’s office on an investigation into two drug rings importing from Mexico that resulted in 10 arrests and the seizure of more than $8.7 million worth of heroin and cocaine. The drug bust was one of the largest in county history.

fields.name: RUSSELL W. HARTIGAN
fields.bio: Russell Hartigan served as a Circuit Court judge from 2010 to 2016, when he stepped down due to family health issues. He served by appointment for two years, then was elected in 2012. During his tenure as a judge, Hartigan served in the First Municipal Division, where he presided over civil cases. Prior to his appointment to the bench, Hartigan worked in private practice for over 30 years, specializing in civil litigation including casualty and municipal defense, workers compensation and personal injury. He also served in several elected and appointed government roles in the suburbs of Berwyn, Lyons, and Western Springs. Since stepping down from the bench, he served for a year as the president of the Illinois State Bar Association.

fields.name: Dear Candidate: Are you a Communist?
JAMES SAMUEL WORLEY
fields.bio: James Samuel Worley is an attorney at Gottreich, Grace & Thompson, where he specializes in family law and DUI criminal defense. Before joining his current firm, he ran his own firm, J. Samuel Worley, LLC. Worley began his legal career as an assistant state’s attorney, and he is currently also an attorney for the Fraternal Order of Police.

fields.name: JILL ROSE QUINN
fields.bio: Jill Quinn is an attorney in private practice, working in a wide range of areas of law, including bankruptcy, family law, and criminal defense. Before running her own practice, Quinn worked for the Village Attorney of Glen Ellyn and as an arbitrator in both DuPage and Cook counties. She ran unsuccessfully for a 10th subcircuit seat in 2018.
fields.notable: If elected, Quinn would become the first transgender judge in Illinois. Quinn is the Democratic Party’s slated candidate.

fields.name: WENDELIN "WENDI" DeLOACH
fields.bio: Wendelin DeLoach is an attorney in private practice, where she works in a wide range of legal areas, including criminal defense, family law and personal injury. She has been licensed to practice in Illinois since 2007 and practiced in Colorado in the early 1990s.
fields.notable: DeLoach was given a 30 day suspension in Colorado in 1997 for representing a client in a murder case when she had previously represented a co-defendant in a separate matter. She used that relationship to visit the co-defendant several times in jail without his lawyer’s knowledge or approval.

fields.name: FELICIA H. SIMMONS-STOVALL
fields.bio: Felicia H. Simmons-Stovall has worked as an enforcement attorney at the Illinois Securities Department for over a decade. On her campaign website, she describes her role as representing the Illinois Secretary of State against “unscrupulous individuals” who commit financial fraud. In addition to her work in consumer protection, Simmons-Stovall has served as an administrative hearing officer for the Illinois Secretary of State. She has previously run twice for alderman in Chicago’s 15th Ward, and lost both times.

fields.name: KELLY MARIE McCARTHY
fields.currentJob: Chief of legal resources division of the Cook County Public Defender’s Office
fields.bio: Kelly McCarthy has spent nearly all of her legal career in the Cook County Public Defender’s Office and currently heads the division specializing in appeals and other post-conviction matters. She has worked in several different areas during her time there, including the civil division, the felony trial division and the homicide task force.

11th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 11th subcircuit includes the Northwest Side neighborhoods of Belmont Cragin, Portage Park and Dunning and the suburbs of Oak Park, Maywood, Elmwood Park, River Grove and Rosemont.

fields.name: 15th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 15th subcircuit covers the south and southwest suburbs of Flossmoor, Chicago Heights, Matteson, Oak Forest, Tinley Park, Oak Forest and Orland Park.

fields.name: 14th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 14th subcircuit covers much of the Southwest Side of Chicago, including Bridgeport, Back of the Yards, Little Village, Brighton Park, and Gage Park, and the suburb of Cicero. It is home to the Leighton Criminal Court House and the Cook County Jail at 26th and California.

fields.name: 13th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 13th subcircuit covers the northwest suburbs of Palatine, Schaumburg, Hoffman Estates, South Barrington, and Streamwood.

fields.name: 12th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 12th subcircuit includes the northern suburbs of Winnetka, Glencoe, Northbrook and Wheeling and the northwest suburbs of Des Plaines, Mt. Prospect and Arlington Heights.

fields.name: 10th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 10th subcircuit covers much of the Northwest Side, including North Center, Ravenswood, Albany Park, Jefferson Park, Norwood Park and Edison Park. It also includes parts of Niles and Park Ridge.

fields.name: 9th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 9th subcircuit covers the North Side neighborhoods of Rogers Park and West Ridge and the north suburbs of Evanston, Skokie, Lincolnwood and Wilmette. It is home to the court's Skokie court house.

fields.name: 8th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 8th subcircuit extends north along the lakefront from Chinatown to Edgewater, and includes the South Loop, the Loop, Near North Side, Lincoln Park, Lakeview and Uptown.

fields.name: 6th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 6th subcircuit extends northwest from West Town through Hermosa and north to Ravenswood. It also includes Wicker Park, Bucktown, Logan Square, Avondale and part of Humboldt Park.

fields.name: 7th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 7th subcircuit extends west along the Eisenhower Expressway from the West Loop to the west suburbs of Berwyn, Forest Park and River Forest (but does not include Oak Park). It includes the West Side neighborhoods of Garfield Park, North Lawndale, Homan Square and Austin, and part of West Humboldt Park.

fields.name: 5th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 5th subcircuit extends south from Bronzeville through South Shore and west to West Englewood. It also includes Kenwood, Hyde Park, Washington Park, and Grand Boulevard.

fields.name: 4th Subcircuit
fields.description: The 4th subcircuit includes a large swath of the western suburbs, from Oak Lawn and Chicago Ridge in the south up through Bridgeview, Countryside, La Grange, McCook and as far north as Franklin Park. It is home to the court's Bridgeview court house.

fields.name: 2nd Subcircuit
fields.description: The 2nd subcircuit includes the South Side neighborhoods of Roseland and Pullman and several south suburbs, including Dolton, Riverdale, Dixmoor, Harvey, and Homewood. It is home to the court's Markham Courthouse.

fields.name: 3rd Subcircuit
fields.description: The 3rd subcircuit includes parts of the Southwest Side, including Midway, Marquette Park, Beverly and Mt. Greenwood. It also includes the southwest suburbs of Burbank, Hometown, and Evergreen Park, and the northeast corner of Oak Lawn.

fields.name: 1st Subcircuit
fields.description: The 1st subcircuit includes parts of the south and southeast sides of Chicago, including Chatham, South Chicago, East Side and Hegewisch, as well as the south suburbs of Burnham and Calumet City.

fields.name: CCL Not Recommended
fields.description: The candidate refused to submit their credentials, but the council is not aware of credible information that would justify a “not qualified” rating.

fields.name: CCL Well Qualified
fields.description: The candidate has demonstrated the abilities required of a judge on the relevant court in the areas considered (e.g. fairness, competence, conduct, independence, integrity/character), and excellence in most areas.

fields.name: CCL Qualified
fields.description: The candidate has demonstrated the abilities required of a judge on the relevant court in the areas considered (e.g. fairness, competence, conduct, independence, integrity/character).

fields.name: CCL Not Qualified
fields.description: The candidate has not demonstrated the abilities required of a judge on the relevant court in the areas considered (e.g. fairness, competence, conduct, independence, integrity/character).

fields.name: CCL Highly Qualified
fields.description: The candidate has demonstrated excellence in the abilities required of a judge on the relevant court in all areas considered (e.g. fairness, competence, conduct, independence, integrity/character).
